We recommended that the City Mayor:
a) Require the assigned Inventory Committee to gather and collate all land-related records purporting to CGN’s ownership and ensure that land properties to be transferred to rightful beneficiaries by HSDO are properly identified and earmarked;
b) Prepare a disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements on the recorded cost of the Land pertaining to the HSDO projects which cannot be derecognized yet despite transfer of ownership to beneficiaries and those capitalized costs for land acquisition but not yet registered in the name of CGN;
c) Require the IC on “Roads and Bridges” to timely perform their duties or functions in conducting an actual physical count of PPEs for a specified time, to facilitate proper accounting and reporting and correct classification of fixed properties;
d) Direct the reconciliation of records between the General Services Department (GSD), the City Engineer’s Office (CEO) and the City Accounting Office (CAO) to present accurate property records;

4. Strictly require the department heads to promptly submit the necessary documents on the full consumption of supplies and materials to the City Accounting Office (CAO), to prepare the necessary adjustments before closing its books to avoid overstating the inventory balance. Additionally, direct the concerned department heads to accomplish the RPCI and RPCSP in a timely manner;
5. Direct the GSO to prepare the prescribed reports and other documents in compliance with COA Circular No. 2022-004, and furnish the same to CAO for the reconciliation of semi-expendable properties;
6. Coordinate with the Inventory Committee to establish effective policies on the timely submission of complete documentation and preparation of their respective physical inventory at the end of every semester; and
7. Monitor the progress of the inventory system being developed, allocate the necessary funds, and ensure its full implementation in the ensuing year.

a) CAO to prepare bank reconciliation statements in a timely manner, compliant with COA Circular No. 96-011, for all funds of CGN, as well as coordinate with the CTO in conducting such reconciliations;
b) CAO to reconcile the variances between the accounting records and the bank balances and effect the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the accurate balance of the Cash in Bank-LCCA account;
c) CTO to ensure that payees whose checks are still outstanding be notified to prevent such checks from becoming stale.

15. Instruct all Special Disbursing Officers to timely report their cash advances and ensure complete documentation to prevent delay in the liquidation of such, otherwise impose possible sanctions such as withholding of the payment of any money due to them;
16. Direct the City Accounting Office to strictly ensure that no additional cash advances will be granted to SDOs with outstanding balances, in accordance with Section 89 of PD 1445, and strictly impose sanctions to SDOs in case of non-liquidation of their cash advances; and
17. Instruct the City Accounting Office to reconcile the balances aged more than five years and determine their actual status as well as diligently monitor the account and prevent unliquidated balances from further increasing.

22. Facilitate the creation of an effective procedure in monitoring and enforcing the submission of liquidation reports, progress reports and terminal reports of the projects in coordination with concerned departments of the City as well as ensure that the CAO is duly provided with the related MOA;
23. Require the City Accountant to record receipt of fund transfers only upon ensuring that source documents, particularly, the Memorandum of Agreement are attached to the Journal Voucher as required under COA Circular 2021-001; and
24. Direct the City Treasurer to return the unutilized funds to the NGAs concerned or otherwise request for appropriate authority to use said funds, if deemed appropriate.

32. Instruct the Naga City Development Council (NCDC), BAC, CEO, and other concerned offices to ensure the sustainability of the infrastructure projects and the quality of service and materials from the suppliers contracted with to be used for all the infrastructure projects of the CGN;
33. Ensure the appropriation of the chemicals needed for the operation of the SLF Waste Water Treatment Facility to prevent the facility from being idle and thus maximize its usage; and
34. Properly evaluate and assess the viability of the projects for infrastructure implementation to avoid delays or non-implementation thereof and ensure projects funded under the LDF are supported by the Annual or Supplemental Investment Plan.

37. Direct the NCDRRMC to prepare a comprehensive LDRRMFIP which includes a listing of projects and activities chargeable against the current year LDRRMF appropriation and the unexpended balances from previous years;
38. Direct the CAO and CBO to complete the reconciliation of their records on the available current year and continuing appropriations for LDRRMF so that the accurate amounts are disclosed in the reports and financial statements; and
39. In the implementation of LDRRM projects, consider coordination of the CGN concerned offices (CDRRMO and CEO) with the respective barangays for the proper monitoring and maintenance of the projects, so that these implemented structures will serve the purpose for which they were designed.

46. Require the NCSB to meticulously determine their priority projects and ensure that the indicative timelines were followed according to item 5.1 of the DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, series of 2017 to achieve efficient and effective utilization of funds;
47. Ensure that priority projects to be charged under SEF and LDF are delineated and identified;
48. Require the NCSB to ensure that all projects are awarded and contracted with existing appropriation; and
49. Require the NCSB to secure the needed certification before declaring savings and realigning such to other projects.

50. Ensure that the PPAs in the GPB with mainstreamed GAD Funds are fully implemented to address the gender issues identified and prevent further GAD concerns, and are within the budget; in case there is a need to implement additional PPAs relevant to current gender issues, comply with JMC No. 2013-01 in informing the DILG Regional Office in writing for the changes in the DILG-approved GPB;
51. Strictly direct the Heads of concerned Departments/Offices to timely submit their respective GAD ARs so that the consolidated GAD AR would be complete and accurate, and those unimplemented projects could be subjected to evaluation; and
52. Ensure the employment of the RC scheme on the assignment of a RC code for GAD.

62. Consider placing additional manpower in the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat to assist the BAC during the conduct of its procurement functions as its main support unit;
63. Direct the BAC to ensure completeness and propriety of the required supporting documents for all contracts submitted to COA for review in accordance with COA Circular No. 2009-01 dated February 12, 2009; and
64. Direct the personnel in charge in the submission of contracts and supporting documents to maintain a checklist of required documents for the procurement of infrastructure projects and goods/services to serve as a guide to ensure the completeness of the documents submitted to COA for review.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive ensure and direct the Municipal Accountant to perform the following: 

Conduct a detailed review and analysis of the affected accounts, confirm obligations by confirmation and verify the supporting documents to establish validity of amounts reported; 

Monitor disbursements in the trust fund and keep up to date all balances in the trust fund to avoid future over payment from the fund; 

For the mandatory contributions that were not deducted from employees’ compensation, prepare an analysis of the breakdown of the contribution and coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to bill the said remittances to the employees; and

Initiate the preparation of the necessary documents to facilitate the filing of the LGU’s request for write-off of dormant liabilities in accordance with the guidelines and procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2023-008 and its relevant Annexes.

We recommended and Management agreed through the: 

Sanggunian, Municipal Budget Officer and other responsible offices to prepare and submit Annual Operating Budget for each LEEs that is supported by a BP and SAFSSR;

Sanggunian, LFC or Economic Development Officer if any, to deliberate and prepare a 5-year Business Plan (BP) especially with the newly established LEEs;

LFC to conduct semi-annual review and general examination of cost and accomplishments against performance standards.

We recommended that the LCE: 

Direct the BAC to monitor each procurement activities specified in the Annual Procurement Plan and reflect the information in the Procurement Monitoring Report as well as the timeline on all procurement activities;

Require the End-Users to prepare PPMPs in accordance with the required format provided by the GPPB posted in its website;

Submit copies of the Annual Procurement Plan and Procurement Monitoring Report within the prescribed form and period to the GPPB; and 

Direct the BAC Secretariat to give utmost priority in the procurement activities to expedite the procurement process of the agency as required in the Government Procurement Reform Act.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of the annual physical count of PPEs and Inventories and to complete and reconcile the prepared RPCPPE and RPCI; 

Observe the proper preparation and submission of the duly accomplished PIF listing of all insurable properties and other assets to GIF of GSIS as a basis for the assessment of the general insurance coverage and copy furnish the Office of the Auditor on or before April 30 of each year.

We recommended for the Municipality to coordinate with the provider of the Accounting System and impose the following:

Correct the internal issues presented by the computer system, and make a patch to improve the already existing system;

Request that continuous customer support be easily available whenever issues were presented;

Provide a user manual and incorporate it in the system where any user could access it in case they need help in using the system. If the updating of SL feature is not yet available, then the provider must incorporate it in the system since it is very important in an accounting system; and

Provide safety features in the system. All users of the system and the changes they made must be properly monitored. Users must be provided with certain level of authority as to their capability to access forms, reports, query, and/ or tables.

We recommended and Management agreed that;
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer undertake periodic reconciliation of balances of RPT and SET Receivable accounts per books of accounts with that of the balances per master list of RPT delinquencies to come up with accurate and reconciled RPT and SET Receivable account balances; and
The Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjusting entry after the reconciliation of records.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive ensure that the:
Inventory Committee conducts a comprehensive annual physical count and prepares the required RPCPPE, properly reconciled with the records of the GSO and Municipal Accountant every after conduct of physical count and cause the submission within the deadline set;
Inventory Committee prepares an Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) containing the appraised value of the items for disposal;
Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer to maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards for easy reconciliation of PPE accounts; and
Municipal Accountant, after reconciliation of PPE records, to effect necessary adjusting entries for variances noted, if any, to establish the accuracy of the reported balances of the PPE.
We further recommended that Management avail of the one – time cleansing of PPEs as stated in COA Circular 2020 – 006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with reliable PPE balances.

We recommended and Management agreed to facilitate the conduct of the one – time cleansing of PPE by performing the following:
Identify other departments within the LGU that may have available staff with relevant skills (E.g., record-keeping, accounting, or logistics) who can be temporarily reassigned to assist and focus with the inventory process;
Collaborate with other government agencies that can provide training on inventory management, especially on the full implementation of the One-time Cleansing of PPE Accounts as outlined in COA Circular 2020-006, so that the LGU may be fully aware of the primary guidelines of the said circular;
Reconstitute the Inventory Committee, with members temporarily relieved of their regular duties until the completion of the physical inventory within a clear and agreed-upon timeline;
Ensure that the Inventory Committee assigns a unique Property Number for each PPE item following the required code format in the numbering system as provided in Section 5 of the Circular; and
Ensure that the newly reconstituted Inventory Committee prepare and submit the approved PIP to the COA Audit Team at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of the inventory-taking process.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require all officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances immediately;
Institute appropriate legal sanction against concerned officials or employees, or by withholding/suspension of the salaries of active accountable officers, provided with the latter’s consent;
Send communication to COA – Intelligence and Confidential Fund Audit Unit pertaining to the status of the long – outstanding Confidential and Intelligence Funds (CIF);
Develop a strategic way to expedite liquidation of cash advances of officers and employees who have already died or no longer in service. After exhausting efforts to have these accounts settled and if no other alternative procedures are available, and if warranted, management may file a request for write-off (Except for the balance of cash advances for CIF) following the procedures enunciated in Section 8 of COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and
Comply with the requirements set forth under COA Circular 2016 - 005 dated December 19, 2016, which provides for the Guidelines and Procedures on the Write-off of Dormant Receivable Accounts, Unliquidated Cash Advances, and Fund Transfers of NGAs, LGUs and Government-Owned and Controlled Corporations (GOCCs).

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief executive:
Ensure that the Inventory committee expedite the disposal process for unserviceable assets to prevent further deterioration and decrease of value by performing the following:
Prepare an IIRUP;
Obtain resolutions authorizing disposal and creating an appraisal committee;
Prepare necessary documents as needed, depending on the mode of disposal;
Have the unserviceable properties inspected, and
Have the disposal be approved by the Local Chief Executive.
Implement security measures, such as fencing the motor pool, to protect idle government properties from theft and unauthorized access; and
Ensure the conduct of periodic assessments and monitoring of properties to improve property and supply management by timely disposal of any unserviceable property in accordance with Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Take into consideration the imposition of liquidated damages for those projects that meet the conditions specified in Item 9.1, Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 (Updated as of 15 April 2023); and
Strictly follow and monitor the project timeliness and ensure prompt implementation of the projects by doing the following;
Perform an inspection to ascertain the current status of the project;
Assess and identify the magnitude of any damage or loss; and
Take necessary measures to ensure the prompt completion of the project, in order for the intended recipients to promptly benefit from the projects.

We recommended and Management agreed that;
Moving forward, stop the practice of giving honorarium to LCPC members; and
Abide by the provisions of DILG Circular No. 2012-120 dated July 4, 2012 in creating the LCPC Plan and Budget as well as the actual utilization thereof.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Designate a statistician or at least a focal person assigned for CBMS data collection, preservation and safekeeping;
Prepare or acquire an information system specifically for storing CBMS data;
Allocate funds needed to support the CBMS activities;
Conduct synchronized data collection of CBMS every three years; and
Closely coordinate with the PSA, in the establishment, maintenance and institutionalization of CBMS as a tool for the formulation and implementation of poverty alleviation and development programs.

19. Direct the City Accounting Office and Barangay Accounting Office to closely monitor the fund transfers and establish the timely sending of demand letters for the submission of the necessary reports as prescribed under COA Circular No. 94-013;
20. Instruct the Barangay Accounting Office to update their records to facilitate the reconciliation and identify the status of the projects with the CAO; and
21. Direct the City Accounting Office to ensure the monitoring of the prior year balances that remained unliquidated and prevent such from further increase.

40. Coordinate with the City Engineering Office and follow-up on the communications with the contractor to come up with plans to rectify the noted deficiencies/damages in the structure of the Evacuation Center;
41. Direct the Camp Management Team to ensure that adequate spaces for post sleeping/shelter areas are provided to future occupants/IDPs in the Evacuation Center; and
42. Capacitate the Camp Management Team by providing adequate trainings and seminars to them as required by the DSWD-DILG-DOH-DepEd JMC No. 02, series of 2021.

43. Direct the City Budget Office to review CGN’s Annual Budget and prioritize the allocation of available funding sources, if any, for the additional capital outlay and MOOE relative to the operation of the Leachate Treatment Plant;
44. Direct the Solid Waste Management Office to ensure inclusion in its annual budget proposal of the necessary Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses for the Leachate Treatment Plant to ensure continuous operation of the facility; and
45. Ensure that the projects to be implemented, particularly those that are capital-intensive, are comprehensively studied, planned, and measured, which includes foreseeing incidental expenses as well as MOOE to ascertain ready and optimal usage and/or benefits.

57. Closely coordinate with the CPDO and CEO to adequately and completely monitor the implementation of all planned PPAs of the CGN, and ensure that all PPAs are included in the listing/GPPA Report being submitted to the Audit Team;
58. Through its CEO, ensure that appropriate project signboards which are compliant with the prescribed format and with complete details concerning the PPAs are placed within the project site for public information and validation; and
59. In ensuing periods, establish strict adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 to attain the purpose of achieving transparency and full disclosure of the CGN’s transactions to the public.

We recommended and Management committed to comply and instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Utilize the correct liability account to report all transfers from Philhealth in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009;

Retrieve appropriate documents and check actual liquidation of funds made to PhilHealth and if possible, reconcile records with the Due from LGU account on the PhilHealth books; 

Perform a detailed review and analysis of the affected accounts and prepare the necessary correcting journal entry vouchers to have a fair presentation of the accounts in the financial statements; and

Strengthen accounting controls by performing a regular review on the journal entry and posting in the ledgers made by the accounting staff.

We recommended and Management agreed to

Identify the accounting policy adopted and fully disclose the details or information regarding the accounting policy adopted and the capitalizable borrowing costs in the NTFS in accordance with IPSAS No. 5;

If the alternative treatment was adopted, instruct the municipal finance committee to submit a separate and updated Schedule of Loan Amortization, identify borrowing costs that should be capitalized during the construction period and/or costs necessary to prepare the qualifying asset for its intended use benchmarked on Status of PPA report and prepare necessary adjusting entries thereafter;

If the alternative treatment was adopted, restate the Financial Statements due adoption of accounting policies in accordance with IPSAS 3 - Accounting Policies, Changes in Accounting Estimates and Errors; and

Moving forward, direct the Municipal Accountant to study constantly IFAC publications vis-a-vis COA accounting rules and regulations, and consult with the audit team about the proper implementation whenever possible.

We recommended that Management provide adequate and available resources for the collection and processing of data requirements of the GAD Database. 

Also, we recommended that Management instruct the GFPS to:

Create and institutionalize the GAD Database with adequate and systematically gathered sex-disaggregated data to provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, programming and policy formulation to effectively plan and implement GAD-related PAPs;

Coordinate with the various agencies, departments and barangays in updating of the GAD database to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;

Establish linkage of the existing Community Based Monitoring System (CBMS) Accelerated Poverty Profiling with the GAD sex-disaggregated data or GAD database required under PCW MC No. 2014-05 dated 24 November 2014, to catalyze performance-based gender responsive planning on the basis of a reliable information system.

Ensure that the gender issues contained in the ensuing GPB are based from the results of gender analysis conducted on the GAD Database and/or any other gender analysis tools.

To fortify the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

Institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

Conduct risk assessment; 
Identify critical processes and functions; 
Determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
Conduct risk analysis and impact analysis
Formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
Submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

Direct the HRMO to further enhance the Municipal Capacity Development agenda by incorporating other mandatory training on Public Service Continuity Planning and ensuring participation of the appropriate LGU officials and personnel in the same; and, 

Improve monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the:

Municipal Accountant to perform a detailed review and analysis of the affected accounts and prepare the necessary correcting journal entry vouchers to have a fair presentation of the accounts in the financial statements and to prepare and maintain CIPLCs on a per project basis and to effect the transfer of completed projects from the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts and ensure that proper accounts are used in recording transactions;

Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accounting Office with copies of the report of completed projects and other necessary documents and to investigate CIP projects which has been in the books for several years;

Municipal Treasurer to update and reconcile inventory records; and

Inventory committee created thru an issuance of a written order complete the actual physical count on a specified time frame and submit complete physical inventory report in accordance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual.

We recommended that Management:

Make the necessary adjustments on the remaining seven checks in the GF after verifying on the cause/s of the returned checks.  Likewise, locate the issuer of the other private checks and demand for check replacement;




Stop the practice of using cash collections for check encashments and observe the proper control and procedures in the deposit of collections;

Instruct the preparer of the BRS to communicate any findings to the City Treasurer and the City Accountant for immediate verification and action; and
Follow the procedures in handling returned check deposits as enumerated in the Local Treasury Operations Manual to properly safeguard the interest of the government.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the City Assessor to update and reconcile all real property records under their jurisdiction and ensure that the QRRPA is reconciled with the database in order to furnish the CTO with a more reliable data;
Require the City Treasurer to ensure that the RPTARs are updated based on the submitted database and assessment roll from the City Assessor.
Require the City Treasurer to forward to the City Accountant a copy of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible at the beginning of the year including the master list of RPT delinquencies.
We further recommended and Management agreed to direct the City Accountant to:
Ensure that the duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year is used as the basis to book up the RPT and SET Receivables at the beginning of the year;
Ensure the proper recording of property tax collections by: (i) recognizing the discounts on advance payment, (ii) using the appropriate income accounts, and (iii) refrain from deducting outright the collection of penalties from Receivable and Deferred Income accounts;
Reconcile the RPT/SET Receivables accounts with the City Treasurer’s List of RPT delinquencies; and
Make the necessary adjustments in the books using the following proposed adjusting journal entries below:

We recommended that Management:
File appropriate charges to the erring accountable personnel to recover the loss of government funds.
Adopt the ICSPPS as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2018-003 to strengthen the City’s internal control;
Incorporate in the mandatory seminars of employees about internal controls as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2018-003 so that employees will have appreciation and understanding of their roles in effective internal control structure of the City;
Incorporate in the computerized system control activities that may help prevent or detect fraud such as but not limited to mandatory use of the system generated RCDs;
Consider restructuring the CTO so that proper delineation and segregation of duties and responsibilities will be observed;
Instruct the City Accountant to effect the proposed adjusting journal entries, as shown in Appendix G.3, if warranted.

We recommended that Management improve their compliance with the guidelines so that adequate safeguard and effective/efficient utilization of the funds could be made, by implementing the following courses of action:
Ensure that future receipts of funds or FA are covered with appropriate MOA specifically providing guidelines for project implementation and reporting;
Ensure that future receipts of FA with specific purpose be properly deposited in the Agency’s trust Account;
Ensure the timely submission of liquidation reports to the SA; and
Take appropriate action for FAs in which the stated purpose became no longer implementable/executable either by returning the same to the SA or obtain similar approval from appropriate government agency to apply the fund to other purpose so as to ensure optimum utilization of the funds instead of being held idle.

We recommended that Management:
Provide the detailed breakdown of the contract cost for the consultative assembly to determine the cost per item of the inclusions;
Explain the difference between the proposed number of participants of 300 pax against the actual attendees of 275 pax for the consultative assembly;
Submit the lacking supporting documents and a written justification/ explanation on the noted deficiencies, for the Audit Team’s verification and evaluation, to avoid disallowance in audit; and
We also recommended and Management agreed to direct the accountable officers to liquidate the cash advances immediately and submit the liquidation documents, for the Audit Team’s evaluation.

